  "answer": "The forbidden case is not a genuine counterexample because the target's mechanism does not require that material outputs show observable degradation before collapse. Palace economies facing rising timber costs would prioritize the most symbolically and functionally critical material outputs—monumental architecture and bronze for elite display and military equipment—by reallocating scarce timber away from lower-priority uses (e.g., lower-quality construction, fuel for non-metallurgical purposes, shipbuilding for non-elite trade) and by intensifying labor inputs to maintain quality in prestige goods. The mechanism specifies that transport costs for replacement timber exceeded the surplus extraction capacity, meaning the system collapsed from the fiscal impossibility of sustaining the entire redistributive package, not from a gradual decline in the physical quality of its highest-status products. High-quality architectural timber and bronze could persist right up to the collapse if the palace diverted dwindling resources to maintain them at the expense of other sectors (agricultural terracing, secondary construction, military logistics), thereby hollowing out the broader economic base while preserving the appearance of monumental output. The destruction layers themselves are the collapse horizon; the mechanism predicts that the system broke when the positive feedback between extraction costs and surplus requirements became unsustainable, which could occur abruptly after a threshold was crossed, leaving no extended period of visible material degradation in the archaeological record of elite construction and metalwork."}